SIMPLE: stretch
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stretch
<hw>Stretch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Stretched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Stretching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>strecchen</ets>, AS. <ets>streccan</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>strekken</ets>, G. <ets>strecken</ets>, OHG. <ets>strecchen</ets>,
Sw. <ets>str⟦aum⟧cka</ets>, Dan. <ets>straekke</ets>; cf. AS.
<ets>straeck</ets>, <ets>strec</ets>, strong, violent, G.
<ets>strack</ets> straight; of uncertain origin, perhaps akin to E.
<ets>strong</ets>. Cf. <er>Straight</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
reach out; to extend; to put forth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>stretch</qex> forth his neck long and small.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I in conquest <qex>stretched</qex> mine arm.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To draw out to the full length; to cause to extend
in a straight line; <as>as, to <ex>stretch</ex> a cord or
rope</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to extend in breadth; to spread; to expand;
<as>as, to <ex>stretch</ex> cloth; to <ex>stretch</ex> the
wings</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make tense; to tighten; to distend
forcibly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ox hath therefore <qex>stretched</qex> his yoke in vain.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To draw or pull out to greater length; to strain;
<as>as, to <ex>stretch</ex> a tendon or muscle</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Awake, my soul, <qex>stretch</qex> every nerve.</q>
<rj><qau>Doddridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To exaggerate; to extend too far; <as>as, to
<ex>stretch</ex> the truth; to <ex>stretch</ex> one's
credit</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They take up, one day, the most violent and <qex>stretched</qex>
prerogative.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stretch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stretch
<hw>Stretch</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be extended; to
be drawn out in length or in breadth, or both; to spread; to reach;
<as>as, the iron road <ex>stretches</ex> across the continent; the lake
<ex>stretches</ex> over fifty square miles</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As far as <qex>stretcheth</qex> any ground.</q>
<rj><qau>Gower.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To extend or spread one's self, or one's limbs;
<as>as, the lazy man yawns and <ex>stretches</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be extended, or to bear extension, without
breaking, as elastic or ductile substances.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The inner membrane . . . because it would <qex>stretch</qex> and
yield, remained umbroken.</q> <rj><qau>Boyle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To strain the truth; to exaggerate; <as>as, a man
apt to <ex>stretch</ex> in his report of facts</as>.</def> <mark>[Obs.
or Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To sail by the wind under press
of canvas; <as>as, the ship <ex>stretched</ex> to the
eastward</as>.</def> <rj><au>Ham. Nav. Encyc.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stretch out</b></col>, <cd>an order to rowers to extend
themselves forward in dipping the oar.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stretch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stretch
<hw>Stretch</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Act of stretching, or
state of being stretched; reach; effort; struggle; strain; <as>as, a
<ex>stretch</ex> of the limbs; a <ex>stretch</ex> of the
imagination</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By <qex>stretch</qex> of arms the distant shore to gain.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those put a lawful authority upon the <qex>stretch</qex>, to the
abuse of yower, under the color of prerogative.</q>
<rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A continuous line or surface; a continuous space of
time; <as>as, grassy <ex>stretches</ex> of land</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A great <qex>stretch</qex> of cultivated country.</q> <rj><qau>W.
Black.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But all of them left me a week at a <qex>stretch</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>E. Eggleston.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The extent to which anything may be
stretched.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Quotations, in their utmost <qex>stretch</qex>, can signify no
more than that Luther lay under severe agonies of mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This is the utmost <qex>stretch</qex> that nature can.</q>
<rj><qau>Granville.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The reach or extent of a vessel's
progress on one tack; a tack or board.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Course; direction; <as>as, the <ex>stretch</ex> of
seams of coal</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To be on the stretch</b></col>, <cd>to be obliged to use
one's utmost powers.</cd> -- <col><b>Home stretch</b></col>. <cd>See
under <er>Home</er>, <pos>a.</pos></cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stretcher</ent>⟦br⟧
